</b> Galata Question </b>: <br> Galata, also known as Pera, holds a complicated place in the history of our City. Your ancestor, Emperor Michael VIII Palaiologos granted it to the Genoese in 1267 in accordance with the Treaty of Nymphaeum. They were prohibited from fortifying it, but Latins, as is their habit, disregarded this, and through subsequent expansions of the walls, enlarged the area of their settlement. Our history with Genoese is complicated – on the one hand, they are Christians, fine soldiers and merchants. Their trade makes our City prosperous and a big part of our fleet is crewed by Genoese mercenary captains and sailors. <br> On the other hand, their highest master is coin and they have their own ambitions to enrich themselves and build their own trade empire around the Mediterranean and the Black seas. Pragmatic to the core, they have even on occasion supported the Ottomans, such as before the recent crusade of Varna in 1444, when the Genoese ships transported Sultan Murad’s army across the Bosporus in exchange for one gold piece per soldier. This led to one of the greatest disasters of recent times, when the Christian armies were defeated, emboldening the Turks and exposing Constantinople to the current threat. <br> Today Genoese of Galata see the threat to Constantinople and seem to be ready to indirectly support us, as they have grown concerned about the unchecked power of the Ottomans. However, Galata is not under our direct control and officially it remains neutral, meaning that the Sultan most likely won’t be attacking it, at least not until he deals with us. How should we plan to use Galata in our siege plans?
